					   <td>

			
			
			



<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">
  
		<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
		<tr>
		    <td valign="top">
		     <p><font face="Verdana" size="3"><b>Article Title:</b>&nbsp;</font>
		     <font face="Verdana" size="2">Player Interest - Attacked by the Guides!</font><br>
		     <a href = "../Subscribe.asp?DID=231178" ><font face="Verdana" size="2">[Subscribe to this document]</font></a></p>
			 </td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr><td>&nbsp;</tr><tr>
		
		    <td valign="top"><div style= "padding:4;float: right"> <script language=JavaScript src=http://www.obsidian-tech.com/absolutebm/abmx.aspx?z=26></script></div><p><font face="Verdana" size="2">
		    <Blockquote>
I was on povar server today playing my 6th level Gnome rogue, Knibkin in the Steamfont montains, I grouped with a 15th level wood elf druid, and a 17th level troll warrior.<P>

They accepted me into their party even though I could not recieve exerience, we hunted for 25 minutes.  Then I found a Minotaur Battle Axe on one of the creatures we killed together.  It was an unexpected find, a weapon twice as powerful as my cursed rusty spear.<P>  

I showed off my new acquisition proudly.  But my group demanded I to win chance game or else give up the weapon.  Not about to hand over the most powerful weapon I'd ever laid my hands on, I did the polite thing; excused myself from the group and ran like hell.<P>  

They shouted out about it being unfair. I shout out my best apologies, "sorry hun, comes with the profession".<P>  

Soon, I'm hailed by a guide.  He wants me to return the axe.  He tells me he expects me to do the honest thing.  I tell him to save his morality for the Paladins.  <P>

A second guide comes on, and tells me he understands I stole something.  "Go away" I tell him, nervously.  <P>

"I can't" he says.<P>

I am summoned in before him.<BR>   
I sat and camped.  Cowardly, I know, but I still have the axe.<P>

But hell, What give these guys the right, to try to right all wrongs in the world? <P> 

Leave, the mortals to their own affairs.  A solution however, would be to give the guides the power to authorize a vendetta status, and a reward for hunting down the other character. Ha! me speaking of fairness.<P>

I for one hope they never do it.<P>

Pwwwwwwwwwt. . .<BR>
Knibkin the brave
</blockquote>
Knibkin submitted this interesting story today. Do you feel he was in the right at least possibly from a roleplaying standpoint, or that he messed up and should be banned/suspended? Do you feel guides have the right to make these types of judgment calls in these scenarios? You can share your thoughts on the situation <a href="http://www.everlore.com/MB_SHOW.asp?FID=76&FN=MainHall&SID=7&SN=Everlore&TID=465792&TN=Player+Interest+%2D+Attacked+by+the+Guides%21&CAT=General&SURL=http%3A%2F%2Fwww%2Eeverlore%2Ecom&PL=3">on this thread</a>, or through our news comments section.<P>
		    </font></p>
			 </td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
		     <td valign="top">
		     <br><font face="Verdana" size="2"><b><a href="UserUpdate.asp?id=231178">[Add Comments] Please Add your comments here!</a></b></font><br><hr>
			  </td>
		</tr>

		</table>

	</td>
